{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:32:08.207656+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 6c708c510171c17fee8c35ed6c39e513620500b8)", "id": "lc_2c32e9e2-f2e0-4064-9260-0250da0ff770"}, {"type": "text", "text": "CREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n", "id": "lc_0f695c05-8cf6-4164-a934-5540e8e217bc"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "395d32e0-4a10-4f32-ae41-153453b7be6c", "tool_call_id": "call_c2e123e8cb5f415d83a244e3", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:32:08.207813+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 9a7ab4a43b359ce089e5b88c4f6f7515daa7431c)", "id": "lc_0efc18f2-d5fe-4363-a699-2782263bff42"}, {"type": "text", "text": "CREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n", "id": "lc_3f942ac1-0fea-4606-9f07-86cf3849f7ed"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "d234484d-671e-4261-897d-2138532daf93", "tool_call_id": "call_6705fc6278e944a9b8493c6f", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:32:08.207838+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 890470cbcd8b22c382d09c9d7ffd222ed613ce36)", "id": "lc_3bd91721-8819-4ee6-a41c-c01edaaa63e0"}, {"type": "text", "text": "#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Apply all SQL files under migrations/ to the running pgdev container.\n# Order: filename glob, lexicographic.\nset -euo pipefail\n\nCONTAINER=\"${PGDEV_CONTAINER:-pgdev_db}\"\nDB_USER=\"${POSTGRES_USER:-app}\"\nDB_NAME=\"${POSTGRES_DB:-app}\"\n\n# Note: relies on shell glob expansion ordering, not on `find`.\n# Tested on bash and zsh with default LC_COLLATE.\nfor f in migrations/*.sql; do\n    echo \"Applying $f\"\n    docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\ndone\n", "id": "lc_989a87af-02e5-480c-bc13-af8ab8fd8a58"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "ae65d29e-f4f1-4fdb-ac26-05f951027f41", "tool_call_id": "call_b6029f904c4b456c841f5b52", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:32:50.745533+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have a clear picture. Let me analyze the issue:\n\n**Issue #1** claims that `scripts/apply_migrations.sh` applies migration files in wrong order on macOS APFS with case-folding, causing `003_add_session_index.sql` to run before `002_create_sessions.sql`.\n\n**My analysis of the actual code:**\n\nThe script uses `for f in migrations/*.sql; do` which relies on shell glob expansion ordering. The migration files are:\n- `001_create_users.sql`\n- `002_create_sessions.sql`\n- `003_add_session_index.sql`\n\n**This is likely not a real bug.** Here's why:\n\n1. **All filenames are lowercase** — case-insensitive filesystems don't affect ordering of identical-case names.\n2. **The first differing character between any two migration files is always a digit** (`1` vs `2` vs `3`). Digits sort consistently across virtually all locales and collation rules.\n3. The reporter's proposed workaround (`ls ... | sort`) would produce the same ordering as the glob — `sort` with no flags uses the same locale collation.\n4. The comment in the script already says \"Tested on bash and zsh with default LC_COLLATE\" — the filenames were designed to sort correctly.\n\nThe reported symptom (\"sometimes applies 003 before 002\") is more likely caused by something else in the reporter's environment (e.g., a stale container with pre-existing tables, or a different script being run). The issue title and description misattribute the cause to case-folding/locale.\n\nI'll add a comment with this analysis and label it appropriately.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 2189, "prompt_tokens": 9664, "total_tokens": 11853, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 1346, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 9088, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0021877068, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0002832768, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00190443}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780864328-SGn7Oh2GfK8vYISza5m0", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3c9-2210-74e0-a0f0-b5d2afe1d18a-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T11_R01_C03_A02", "issue_number": 1, "body": "Thanks for the detailed report, @BruceKZ! After reviewing the script and migration filenames, I believe this is **not a bug** in the current codebase. Here's my reasoning:\n\n**The migration filenames are immune to the case-folding/locale issue described:**\n\nThe files are `001_create_users.sql`, `002_create_sessions.sql`, and `003_add_session_index.sql`. The first differing character between any pair is always a **digit** (`1` vs `2` vs `3`). Digits sort consistently across all locales and collation rules — including `en_US.UTF-8` on macOS APFS. Additionally, all filenames are lowercase, so case-insensitive filesystem behavior doesn't apply.\n\n**The proposed workaround wouldn't change behavior:**\n\n`ls migrations/*.sql | sort` produces the same ordering as the bare glob `migrations/*.sql` — both use the same locale collation. If the glob were truly sorting incorrectly, `sort` (without explicit flags) would likely produce the same wrong order.\n\n**Likely root cause of the observed error:**\n\nThe `\"relation \\\"sessions\\\" does not exist\"` error when applying `003_add_session_index.sql` is more likely caused by:\n- A previously failed or partial migration run leaving the database in a state where `sessions` table doesn't exist but `002` was already \"applied\" (e.g., tracked in a migrations history table)\n- The `sessions` table creation in `002` failing silently (e.g., a `REFERENCES users(id)` FK violation if `users` table has issues)\n- A different script or manual operation modifying the database between runs\n\n**Recommendation:** I'd suggest the reporter try a fully clean reset (`docker compose down -v` to remove volumes, then `docker compose up -d`) and verify the error is truly about ordering vs. a dependency issue in `002_create_sessions.sql`.\n\nClosing as not-reproducible / not-a-bug, but happy to reopen if there's a concrete repro that demonstrates the glob ordering is the cause."}, "id": "call_2dd628f3bcb54308a0a35a77", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 9664, "output_tokens": 2189, "total_tokens": 11853, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9088}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1346}}}}]}}}
